{"parse":{"title":"cucumber","pageid":42228,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"==English==\n[[File:Australia_Cucumbers_for_sale_at_store.jpg|thumb|Cucumbers (2)]]\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|cuke|cumber||both|_|colloquial}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|cucumer}}, {{m|enm|cucumber}}, from {{der|en|fro|cocombre}}, ultimately from {{der|en|la|cucumis|cucumis, cucumerem}} (possibly through an {{der|en|pro|-}} intermediate). Probably of Pre-Italic {{der|en|qfa-sub}} origin. {{etydate|late 14c.}} Displaced native {{ncog|en|earthapple}} (see which for more), which has since acquired other senses.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{a|en|non-rhotic}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈkjuːˌkʌmbə/|[ˈkʰjʊu̯ˌkʰʌmbə]|a=RP}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈkjuːˌkʊmbə/|[ˈkʰjʊu̯ˌkʰʊ̈mbə]|a=Northern England,non-foot-strut split}}\n* {{a|en|rhotic}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈkjuˌkʌmbɚ/|[ˈkʰjʊu̯ˌkʰʌ̈mbɚ]|~|[ˈkʰjʊu̯ˌkʰʌ̈mbɹ̩]|a=GA}}\n*** {{audio|en|En-us-cucumber.ogg|a=US}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈkjʉˌkʌmbəɹ/|[ˈkjʉˌkʌmbəɹ]|a=Scotland}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈkaʊˌkʌmbəɹ/|[ˈkʰaʊ̯ˌkʰʌmbəɹ]|a=obsolete|ref2={{R:Hall PGSMS|1|10|38}} !!! {{R:en:Ross:1970|page=72}} !!! {{R:CPD|Cucumber|198|ip=1}}}}\n* {{rhyme|en|ʌmbəɹ|s=3}}\n* {{hyph|en|cu|cum|ver}}\n* {{hmp|en|Qcumber}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# A [[vine]] in the [[gourd]] family, {{taxfmt|Cucumis sativus|species}}.\n#* {{quote-book|en|page=326|author=A Lady [Hannah Glasse]|year=1767|title=The Art of Cookery Made Plain and Eaſy{{...}}|url= https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=pd5QAQAAIAAJ |passage=ASPARAGUS, cauliflowers, imperial Sileſia, royal and cabbage lettuces, burnet, purſlain, '''cucumbers''', naſturtian flowers, peaſe and beans ſown in October, artichokes, ſcarlet ſtrawberries, and kidney beans. }}\n# {{senseid|en|Q2735883}}The [[edible]] [[fruit]] of this [[plant]], having a [[green]] [[rind]] and [[crisp]] [[white]] [[flesh]].\n#: {{syn|en|cuke|q1=informal|cumber|id2=cucumber|q2=colloquial}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1785|quotee=w:Samuel Johnson|title=Journal of a Tour to the Hebrides with Samuel Johnſon{{...}}|author=w:James Boswell|publisher=Henry Baldwin|location=London|page=356|url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=E0JAAAAQAAJ|passage={{...}}for it has been a common ſaying of phyſicians in England, that a '''cucumber''' ſhould be well ſliced, and dreſſed with pepper and vinegar, and then thrown out, as good for nothing.}}\n#* {{RQ:Landon Ethel Churchill|page=14|volume=II|passage=\"Why, pepper and salt your reasons!\" cried Curl, forgetting to look at the door for a moment: \"your pamphlet has talent; but talent is like a '''cucumber''', nothing without the dressing. You must be more personal.\"}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1961|author=Harry E. Wedeck|title=Dictionary of Aphrodisiacs|publisher=The Citadel Press|location=New York|page=71|passage=Probably on account of its phallic formation, the '''cucumber''' is often assumed to have aphrodisiac qualities.}}\n#* {{RQ:NYT|date=12 March 2025|author=David Tanis|title=Cucumber-Cabbage Salad With Sesame|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20250313124746/https://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/1026666-cucumber-cabbage-salad-with-sesame|passage=To the bowl, add '''cucumber''', cabbage and carrot.}}\n# {{lb|en|informal|figurative}} A person who is [[calm]] and [[self-possessed]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1986|title=Linking Technology and Users|author=|page=41 passage=Just a few tips will help even the most anxious of us get a bit of control over the presentation of information and thus appear to be that \"'''cool cucumber'''\" in cognito!}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1999|title=The Brewery |author=Mark Grantham|page=275|passage=The guy's a real '''cucumber'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2002|title=Putting on Mock Trials |author=Margaret Fisher|page=29| passage=That Wolf is one cool '''cucumber'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2018|title=American By Day|author=Derek B. Miller| page=65|passage=\"You're smart,\" says Irv, pointing at her and nodding his head. \"A smart '''cucumber'''.\"}}\n\n====Coordinate terms====\n{{col|en\n|courgette\n|gherkin\n|marrow\n|pickle\n|squash\n|zucchini\n}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|en|title=Affixed and blended forms\n|cucumberade\n|cucumber time\n|cucumber tree\n|cucumber fish,cucumberfish|cucumber mosaic virus\n|cucumber beetle\n|cucumberita\n|cucumbertini\n}}\n{{col4|en|title=derived terms\n|Qcumber\n}}\n{{col4|en|title=Expressions with this term at the beginning\n|cucumberlike\n|cucumbery|\ncucumberless| cucumber herring|cucumber mullet\n|cucumberish\n}}\n{{col4|en|title=Expressions with this term at the middle or end\n|collapse=n\n|spotted cucumber beetle\n|aardvark cucumber\n|burr cucumber\n|gemsbok cucumber\n|striped cucumber beetle\n|stuffing cucumber\n|Armenian cucumber\n|bitter cucumber\n|calm as a cucumber\n|telegraph cucumber\n|cool as a cucumber\n|devil's cucumber\n|exploding cucumber\n|maroon cucumber\n|sea cucumber\n|serpent cucumber\n|slicing cucumber\n|smacked cucumber\n|snake cucumber\n|squirting cucumber\n|star cucumber\n|wild cucumber\n|yard-long cucumber\n|zombie's cucumber\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|en|cucumiform}} {{gloss|cucumber-shaped}}\n\n====Descendants====\n{{top3}}\n* {{desc|tpi|kukamba}}\n* {{desc|chr|ᎦᎦᎹ|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|kw|kukomber|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|crk|kohkompaninawak|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|sm|kukama|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|es|cacombra|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|cy|ciwcymbr|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|zu|îkhukhámba|bor=1}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|plant}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|kastravec}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|خِيَار|m}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|خيار|m|tr=xeyār}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|خيار|tr=ḵyār}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{t|aii|ܚܝܼܵܪܵܐ|tr=ḳīyara|m}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|վարունգ}}\n* Assamese: {{t|as|তিয়ঁহ|tr=tiõh}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|pepinu|m}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|xiyar}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|ҡыяр}}\n* Basque: {{t|eu|luzoker}}\n* Belarusian: {{t+|be|агуро́к|m}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|кра́ставица|f}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|သခွား}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|cogombre|m}}, {{t|ca